    {
      "id": "ml98p6qq",
      "questionNumber": 10,
      "questionText": "<p>Grignard reagent $\\mathrm{RMgBr}(\\mathrm{P})$ reacts with water and forms a gas $(\\mathrm{Q})$. One gram of Q occupies $1.4 \\mathrm{dm}^3$ at STP. (P) on reaction with dry ice in dry ether followed by $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$forms a compound (Z). 0.1 mole of (Z) will weigh $\\_\\_\\_\\_$ g. (Nearest integer)</p>",
      "options": [],
      "correctOption": 0,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "preparation-properties-and-uses-of-carboxylic-acids",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p>With water, a Grignard reagent gives the corresponding hydrocarbon:</p>\n<p>$ \\mathrm{RMgBr + H_2O \\rightarrow RH\\ (Q) + Mg(OH)Br} $</p>\n<p>Given 1 g of $Q$ occupies $1.4\\,\\text{dm}^3$ at STP.</p>\n<p>Moles in $1.4\\,\\text{dm}^3$:</p>\n<p>$ n=\\frac{1.4}{22.4}=0.0625\\ \\text{mol} $</p>\n<p>So molar mass of $Q$:</p>\n<p>$ M=\\frac{1}{0.0625}=16\\ \\text{g mol}^{-1} $</p>\n<p>A hydrocarbon gas with molar mass 16 is methane, $\\mathrm{CH_4}$. Hence $R=\\mathrm{CH_3}$, and $P=\\mathrm{CH_3MgBr}$.</p>\n<p>Carboxylation with dry ice followed by acid workup gives:</p>\n<p>$ \\mathrm{CH_3MgBr \\xrightarrow[ether]{CO_2} CH_3COO^{-}MgBr \\xrightarrow{H_3O^+} CH_3COOH\\ (Z)} $</p>\n<p>So $Z$ is acetic acid, $\\mathrm{CH_3COOH}$, with molar mass $60\\ \\text{g mol}^{-1}$.</p>\n<p>Mass of $0.1$ mol:</p>\n<p>$ 0.1 \\times 60 = 6\\ \\text{g} $</p>\n<p><strong>Answer: 6 g</strong></p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
